A14:
I would recommend reconsidering how you have worded your questions about gender and sexual orientation.
For instance, it is in my view (as someone with a personal stake in the matter) not ideal to ask about gender or orientation in terms of what one "identifies with". This can have an unfortunate implication that one is not 'really' that gender, despite other intentions. Furthermore, 'divers' and non-binary have considerable overlap. Actually, divers typically refers to intersex people (sex assignment at birth) rather than the social variable gender. It is strange to have both when you want to target social gender, presumably. One idea for the future would be to word the question as: What is your gender (identity)? With: Man, woman, non-binary, I prefer to self identify (supply option) and I prefer not to state. If you are interested, you could then additionally ask people if they would like to be put into trans category for the purposes of this research. If you are interested in 'diversity' this is probably useful, since the way your survey is set up now trans people are made invisible.
